				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Sage is a horrible artisan subclass.  You must have Alchemist (ink) and Woodworker (paper, quills) alts or friends, or else it is impossible to advance.  People charge an arm and a leg for ink, paper, and quills in the market, because (a) they are tedious, low XP recipes and (b) they can since no one else can sell them.
<br />

<br />
I am leveling up a Sage at the moment to help supply Armorer and Tailor friends with patterns for their craft.  I already have an Alchemist alt to make myself inks, but it looks like I am going to have to level up a Woodworker alt too for the paper and quills.  My Provisioner (Craftsman) can make the cailun paper and maple quills good up to 19, but 20+, Woodworkers on my server charge nosebleed prices for tapa paper and ash quills.
<br />

<br />
That is one subclass and two alts just to be viable 20+, which is nuts.  Thankfully, with the way Vitality experience works, you can switch between alts and get bonus experience while working on each character.
<br />

<br />
With the change to the way spells are scribed, they should give Sages the ability to make crude paper and quills and shaped inks so at least they could level themselves up.  They would still have to buy pristine inks from Alchemists to make Apprentice III and IV spells, but at least they could grind artisan XP on Apprentice IIs they can make all by themselves.
<br />

<br />
They really need to do this across the board for all the artisan classes.  Right now, Alchemists and Provisioners (note which two I play) are the only self-sufficient classes who can survive without needing another class (usually an Alchemist) to advance.  Everyone else is at the mercy of the higher level artisans.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
