			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Well, in this case, they actually fixed the issues with the vitality bars before putting them live.  They were not updating properly on Test prior to the big patch, but they seem to be working on Live.
<br />

<br />
I have a routine I go through for my Sage-Alchemist-Woodworker trio that works out well.
<br />

<br />
1A) Make 20 resins, 40 oils, and 60 washes using 30 roots (5+10+15).
<br />
2A) Make 20 inks using these oils and washes.
<br />
3W) Make 20 paper and 20 quills using these oils, resins, and washes.
<br />
4S) Make 20 scrolls using these inks, paper, and quills.
<br />

<br />
Doing the combines in this order works out well so that by the time I get around to doing combines again on someone, the Vitality that they consumed from the last go-around will have refreshed.
<br />

<br />
I harvest massive amounts weekend mornings when fewer people are on and use those resources during the week.
<br />

<br />
That's 90 Alchemist combines, 60 Woodworker combines, and 20 Sage combines, which will pretty much take an entire evening.  The Alchemist combines can be harrowing, since the way I do them, they have to all be pristine to maximize resource utilization.  The Sage and Woodworker combines can be any quality though I make an effort to make pristines to get as much experience as possible from the combines.
<br />

<br />
If you want to make money as an artisan, I recommend Provisioner or Alchemist.  You don't have to bug or pay anyone else for your subcombines, and you can either do workshop tasks (Provisioner) or sell to NPC (Alchemist) for large amounts of coin.  My Provisioner's made a few platinum doing Tier 4 and 5 tasks, and my Alchemist easily supports himself by selling sub-pristine ink and ink subcombines to vendor.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
